  <div class="content">
        <p>My experience transforming Linux key bindings to better suit the familiarity of a Mac OS user. By leveraging the power of GNOME Tweaks and Terminal commands, I successfully swapped key positions and redefined essential shortcuts.</p>

        <h2>Swapping Ctrl and Alt</h2>
        <p>My first step was to bring the familiarity of Mac OS to Linux by switching the positions of Ctrl and Alt keys. Using GNOME Tweaks, I effortlessly adjusted the keyboard layout to align with my muscle memory, making the transition smoother and more enjoyable.</p>

        <img src="static/images/ktweaks.png" alt="nvim" width="700" height="600">

        <h2>Redefining Shortcuts</h2>
        <p>In the pursuit of a seamless experience, I decided to redefine copy and paste shortcuts. Navigating to Terminal preferences, I edited the shortcuts to mirror the Mac OS conventions â€“ Ctrl+C for copy and Ctrl+V for paste. This small tweak made a significant impact on my daily workflow.</p>

        <img src="static/images/prefrences.png" alt="nvim" width="700" height="600">

        <h2>To Conclude</h2>
        <p>In the realm of personalizing my Linux experience, my journey was driven by a desire to make the operating system uniquely mine. Through swapping key positions and redefining essential shortcuts, I believe I have successfully molded my Linux environment to align with some of my Mac OS-centric workflow, creating an environment that feels like an extension of my computing history.</p>      
